extends layout.pug

block content
  main.page
    article.prose
      header.prose-header
        p.eyebrow About
        h1 The story behind Flickerdocs
      section
        p.lede I built this real-time collaborative editor without any framework, AI assist, or central server — just a CRDT and WebRTC.
        p I wanted to code without a framework. To feel the code and the computer the way it was in the 1970s, when C and Unix were new and programs talked directly to the hardware. The interest is in zeros and ones — not the framework-of-the-month that everyone learns and then forgets where any of it came from.

        h2 Who I am
        p I'm Chinmay. I've built and sold a couple of startups, all in core tech. What I keep coming back to: robotics, hard systems problems, pure code.

        h2 Why I built this
        ul
          li Reading distributed-systems papers is one thing. Building one is another.
          li I wanted to understand CRDTs from primitives — not by reaching for Yjs.
          li Real-time collaboration without a central server is one of the genuinely hard problems. Worth picking.

        h2 What I learned
        ul
          li Version vectors track causality, not position. Position is what fractional identifiers do.
          li Fractional identifiers + siteIds make concurrent inserts at the same position resolve deterministically — no coordinator needed.
          li The math is the easy part. Making remote cursors glide smoothly while the doc underneath is being edited by someone else is the hard part.

        h2 Tech stack
        ul
          li #[strong CRDT] — custom Logoot-family fractional identifiers + version vectors
          li #[strong WebRTC] via PeerJS for peer-to-peer transport
          li #[strong CodeMirror 5] as the editor surface
          li #[strong Express] + Pug for serving + signaling
          li #[strong Vanilla JS] — no React, no framework, no build assist

        h2 The honest bit
        p For a real product I'd reach for Yjs. I built this from scratch because I wanted to understand the primitives — not because I'd ship this exact code. Knowing the design space matters more than the code.

